Publicly Available Satellite Imagery Sources
NASA Earth Observation Data â€“ NASA provides extensive free satellite imagery through programs like the Earth Observing System. Data from NASA missions (e.g. MODIS on Terra/Aqua, VIIRS on Suomi NPP, and others) are openly available via NASAâ€™s Earthdata portal and APIsâ€‹
EARTHDATA.NASA.GOV
. NASAâ€™s Global Imagery Browse Services (GIBS) and Worldview interface offer over 1,200 global, full-resolution imagery layers, updated daily for near-real-time monitoringâ€‹
EARTHDATA.NASA.GOV
. Spatial resolutions and revisit times vary by instrument â€“ for example, MODIS provides ~500m to 1km resolution daily, while the joint NASA/USGS Landsat missions (see below) provide 15â€“30m resolution imagery every 16 days. Data access is provided through REST APIs, OPeNDAP, and download services. For instance, NASAâ€™s Earth Imagery API (powered by Google Earth Engine) allows on-demand retrieval of Landsat 8 imagery by latitude/longitude and dateâ€‹
API.NASA.GOV
. Historical vs. real-time: NASA archives span decades (e.g. Landsat since 1972) and also support near-real-time feeds â€“ certain datasets (like MODIS near-real-time fire or flood data) are available within hours of acquisition via NASAâ€™s LANCE system. All NASA-provided Earth imagery is free and open to the public (often requiring a free Earthdata login for API access). ESA Sentinel-2 (Copernicus) â€“ The European Sentinel-2 constellation provides high-resolution optical imagery (10mâ€“20m) on a global scale. Sentinel-2 consists of two satellites with a 5-day revisit at the equator, carrying 13 spectral bands (10 m resolution in four visible/NIR bands, 20 m in six bands, 60 m in three atmospheric bands)â€‹
DATASPACE.COPERNICUS.EU
. Data availability: Sentinel-2 data is systematically and freely available to all users (public, scientific, commercial)â€‹
DATASPACE.COPERNICUS.EU
. The mission has been operating since 2015, and its data archive is accessible through the Copernicus Open Access Hub (now replaced by the Copernicus Data Space Ecosystem) and cloud platforms (e.g. Amazon S3 bucket under the AWS Open Data program). Access methods include RESTful APIs and download services â€“ for example, the Copernicus API allows searching by area, time, and cloud cover, and returns download links for imagery. Python libraries like sentinelsat can automate Sentinel-2 search and download. The Sentinel Hub API (commercial, but with free tiers) also provides convenient access, including on-the-fly processing. Near-real-time vs. historical: Sentinel-2 imagery is typically available within 24 hours of acquisition for Level-1C products; higher-level processed imagery (Level-2A surface reflectance) may have slightly longer latency. The entire archive from mission start is available for historical analysis. This combination of frequent revisit and open data makes Sentinel-2 a backbone for monitoring changes (vegetation, infrastructure, etc.) related to troop movements or conflict over time. USGS/NASA Landsat â€“ The Landsat program offers the longest continuous record of Earthâ€™s land imagery, now freely available. Landsat 8 and 9 (current as of 2023) collect global multispectral images at 30 m resolution (visible, NIR, SWIR) with a 185 km swath, plus a 15 m panchromatic band and 100 m thermal bandsâ€‹
LANDSAT.GSFC.NASA.GOV
. The revisit for a given location is 16 days per satellite; with two satellites, most places update every ~8 days. Data access: All Landsat data are public domain and distributed by USGS via platforms like EarthExplorer, USGS API, or the AWS Open Data Registryâ€‹
LANDSAT.GSFC.NASA.GOV
. Users can query by date, location, and cloud cover to retrieve images (GeoTIFF files). Landsat data can also be accessed programmatically (e.g. using the USGS EarthExplorer API or Google Earth Engine for large-scale analyses). Historical data: the archive spans back to 1972 (Landsat 1) â€“ invaluable for historical troop site analysis (e.g. comparing current vs. past imagery of bases or terrain). Near-real-time: New Landsat scenes are available within a day of capture in most cases (initial â€œTier 1â€ products often within hours). While Landsatâ€™s revisit is coarser than Sentinelâ€™s, its long-term record is excellent for training models on decades of historical data and detecting long-term patterns in conflict zonesâ€‹
LANDSAT.GSFC.NASA.GOV
. Maxar Commercial Imagery â€“ Maxar Technologies (formerly DigitalGlobe) operates high-resolution commercial Earth-imaging satellites. Their platforms (WorldView-1/2/3/4, GeoEye-1, etc.) capture imagery up to 0.3 m (30 cm) spatial resolution, currently the best available to the publicâ€‹
MAXAR.COM
. Maxar was the first to deliver native 30 cm resolution and even offers 15 cm â€œHDâ€ images via algorithmic enhancementâ€‹
MAXAR.COM
. Data availability: Unlike the above programs, Maxarâ€™s recent imagery is commercial â€“ users typically purchase data or subscriptions (e.g. through Maxarâ€™s SecureWatch platform or APIs). Public access is limited to what Maxar releases for free or what customers (like news agencies) publish. Notably, Maxar runs an Open Data Program for humanitarian crises, releasing before-and-after imagery of major disasters or conflicts under Creative Commons licensingâ€‹
MAXAR.COM
. For example, during the Ukraine war, Maxar publicly released satellite images of troop convoys and battlefield locations used by media and analysts (these images were made available in the public domain for awareness and humanitarian analysis). Access methods: Paying customers and partners can use Maxarâ€™s APIs to task satellites, stream imagery, or download archive data (Maxar maintains a 125+ petabyte archive of imageryâ€‹
MAXAR.COM
). The company also provides web services (WMTS, WMS) for developers integrating imagery into GIS applications. Real-time vs. historical: Maxar can acquire new imagery on-demand (often used for near-real-time intelligence, with satellites taskable to capture specific sites). However, the general public sees these only when released. Historically, Maxarâ€™s archive (spanning roughly 2000sâ€“present) can be tapped for training data if one has access â€“ for example, older high-res images can be purchased or sometimes found in public repositories (Google Earthâ€™s imagery mosaics use a lot of Maxar data, albeit not in raw form). In summary, Maxar data provides the highest detail (able to identify vehicles, large equipment, etc.), but integration into a pipeline usually requires handling licensing or using their open releases for events. Real-Time vs Historical Data Considerations: In integrating satellite imagery for troop movement analysis, a common approach is to use historical imagery to train models (e.g. detect presence of military infrastructure or changes over time), and then apply the model on near-real-time imagery to predict or detect current movements. Public satellites like Sentinel-2 and Landsat provide consistent, long-term archives and global coverage, ideal for training and broad situational awareness. Higher-resolution imagery (commercial or classified, discussed next) can provide detailed validation data or be used in focused areas. Keep in mind the trade-offs: free sources have lower resolution but frequent, open coverage; commercial/military sources have high detail but limited accessibility.
Future Integration with Government/Military Satellites
In addition to public data, there is interest in integrating government or military-grade satellite imagery (e.g. U.S. National Reconnaissance Office satellites) into analysis pipelines. Current spy satellites operated by NRO and other agencies reportedly achieve even higher resolutions than commercial Maxar imagery (exact capabilities are classified). They produce GEOINT (geospatial intelligence) that is used internally by militaries for real-time troop tracking, but these feeds are not publicly available. For example, the NROâ€™s fleet (e.g. the KH-series satellites) remains secret and their imagery is classified â€“ the public typically only sees such data when declassified years later or shared in rare public releases. A historical case is the CORONA reconnaissance program: it was declassified after the Cold War, releasing over 860,000 images from 1960â€“1972 into the public domainâ€‹
USGS.GOV
. This shows that integration of military imagery becomes possible once data is declassified, but there is a long lag. Future possibilities: if government agencies decide to share more data (perhaps at reduced resolution or with a delay), those could be integrated similarly to commercial sources. Already, there is some collaboration â€“ for instance, the NRO now contracts with commercial providers like Maxar for imageryâ€‹
EOPORTAL.ORG
, blurring lines between government and commercial data. In a forward-looking scenario, one could imagine a pipeline where classified real-time feeds are ingested (behind secure systems) to provide up-to-the-minute troop positions to a model. In the public domain, however, we must mostly rely on the open sources discussed above. Nonetheless, keeping the pipeline design flexible for â€œfuture integrationâ€ is wise: e.g. designing data schemas that could accommodate higher-resolution or more frequent imagery when available. For now, practitioners sometimes use declassified imagery (like CORONA or other released spy photos) to augment training data â€“ useful for historical analysis or to train models on varied imaging sources (different look angles, film images, etc.). In summary, military-grade data offers great potential for more precise tracking, but until access improves, it remains a theoretical addition for public ML pipelines.
Geospatial Intelligence Data Sources (Troop Movements)
Beyond raw imagery, structured geospatial data about conflict events and troop movements is crucial. Two notable sources are DeepStateMap and ACLED, which provide reliable, structured information on military operations: DeepStateMap â€“ DeepStateMap.live is an open-source intelligence (OSINT) project and interactive online map that tracks military operations in the Russia-Ukraine warâ€‹
EN.WIKIPEDIA.ORG
. Launched on 24 Feb 2022 by a volunteer team (â€œDeep State UAâ€), it is updated regularly with frontline changes, territorial control, and reported troop movements. The map blends visual evidence with vetted reports from Ukrainian military sourcesâ€‹
EN.WIKIPEDIA.ORG
. In practice, DeepStateMap shows which areas are occupied by which side, often down to villages, and marks advances/retreats (for example, areas recently liberated are highlighted in green, occupied areas in red on the map). This provides a near real-time, human-curated dataset of troop positions and frontlines. For integration, DeepStateMap offers an API (used with permission by third-party apps) to fetch the latest map dataâ€‹
GITHUB.COM
â€‹
GITHUB.COM
. The API returns geo-objects (such as polygons of control areas, front line vectors, and possibly unit locations) that can be converted into machine-readable features. In a pipeline, one could query DeepStateMapâ€™s API periodically to get the latest frontline geometry and changes, and use that as input data for modeling troop movement. For example, you might compute the shift of the front line over time as a numeric feature (distance moved per day in a sector) or classify areas as â€œcontestedâ€ vs â€œsecureâ€ based on the map. Because DeepStateMap is focused on a single conflict, it provides high-detail, high-accuracy data for that theater â€“ useful for training models on real troop movement patterns (e.g. to predict where advances might occur next). Itâ€™s essentially a ground-truth dataset for the Ukraine war, constructed from OSINT. Outside of Ukraine, similar community-driven maps are less common, but the approach could be generalized (for instance, Syrian civil war maps or others, though not as systematic as DeepStateMap). ACLED (Armed Conflict Location & Event Data Project) â€“ ACLED is a widely used structured database of political violence and conflict events worldwide. It records dates, locations (usually coordinates within a province or town), actors involved, event types, and casualties for conflict eventsâ€‹
EN.WIKIPEDIA.ORG
. Crucially, ACLED includes not just battles and violence, but also â€œnon-violent conflict eventsâ€ such as strategic troop movements, protests, and territorial transfersâ€‹
DANTE-PROJECT.ORG
. This means ACLED can provide data points for troop movements (e.g. a record of â€œArmed forces of X country withdrew from town Y on date Zâ€ would appear as a coded event). ACLED is updated in near real-time: new events are added weekly, based on a wide range of sources and rigorous verificationâ€‹
PYTHON.PLAINENGLISH.IO
. As of recent years, ACLED has global coverage (with detailed coverage of Africa, Middle East, Asia, Europe, Latin America, etc.) and over a million event recordsâ€‹
EN.WIKIPEDIA.ORG
. Data availability: ACLED data is free for non-commercial use; users must register for an API token or download datasets. An API is provided to query events by parameters like country, date range, event type, etc., returning results in JSON or CSV. For example, one can query all events in 2023 in Ukraine, or all â€œBattleâ€ events in a certain province. This structured data is extremely useful for machine learning â€“ you can aggregate events to form features (like â€œnumber of conflict events in region X in past weekâ€) or use the event types as labels (e.g. to train a model to predict the likelihood of a â€œtroop movementâ€ event occurring in a given area). ACLEDâ€™s schema includes fields like event date, location (with geocoordinates), event type (battle, riot, strategic development, etc.), involved actors, and a free-text â€œnotesâ€ field describing the eventâ€‹
PYTHON.PLAINENGLISH.IO
. The structured fields enable straightforward integration into a database or Pandas DataFrame for analysis. Example: Using ACLEDâ€™s API to fetch data â€“ we can retrieve events and integrate them into a pandas DataFrame for analysis:
python
Copy
Edit
import requests
import pandas as pd

# Example: fetch recent battle events in Ukraine from ACLED (requires API token from ACLED)
api_url = "https://api.acleddata.com/ACLED/read"
params = {
    "country": "Ukraine",
    "event_type": "Battles",   # filter for battle events (including armed clashes)
    "year": "2023",
    "token": "<YOUR_API_TOKEN>"  # API token obtained from ACLED registration
}
response = requests.get(api_url, params=params)
data = response.json()

# Load results into a DataFrame
events_df = pd.DataFrame(data.get('data', []))
print(events_df.columns)  # see available fields
print(events_df[['event_date', 'location', 'event_type', 'actor1', 'actor2']].head())
In this snippet, we query ACLED for battle events in Ukraine in 2023. The resulting JSON is loaded into a DataFrame, yielding structured columns like event_date, location (e.g. village or district name), actor1 and actor2 (the primary warring parties), etc. Each row represents a specific incident or movement. We could similarly pull â€œStrategic developmentsâ€ or â€œNon-violent troop activityâ€ event types to specifically get troop movement entries (ACLED often codes things like troop mobilization or relocation under such categories)â€‹
DANTE-PROJECT.ORG
. This structured event data can then be merged with other data (e.g. satellite imagery or geospatial grids) by location and date. Beyond DeepStateMap and ACLED, other geospatial intelligence sources include:
LiveUA Map (another live conflict mapping platform, for Ukraine and other conflicts, though more news-aggregated),
GDELT (discussed below, an automated global event database),
U.S. DoD reports or NATO releases (often unstructured text but can be parsed for info), and
Historical conflict datasets like UCDP (Uppsala Conflict Data Program) which provide geocoded conflict events, though typically focusing on violence rather than movements.
The combination of satellite imagery (for physical verification) and structured intelligence data (for context and labeling) is powerful. For instance, DeepStateMap can tell you where fronts are moving, and satellite images can show what is on the ground in those locations; ACLED can provide a timeline of conflict events that a model might try to predict or correlate with satellite-observed changes. These sources serve as training data for supervised learning (e.g. classifying an image as â€œtroop presenceâ€ vs â€œno troop presenceâ€ using labels from ACLED/DeepState) or as supplementary features in a predictive model (e.g. using the count of recent events from ACLED as an input feature to predict future movements).
Tracking Real-Time News Reports on Troop Movements (NLP & Automation)
Another key component is ingesting real-time news reports of troop movements. Media reports, official statements, and social media can provide immediate information on military activity. However, this data is unstructured text that must be extracted, filtered, and processed to be useful for a model. Best practices include:
Automated data extraction using NLP: Tools from natural language processing can identify relevant information in news text. For example, named entity recognition (NER) can find location names, organizations (military units), and dates in a report, and relation extraction or event detection algorithms can categorize the event (e.g. detect that it describes a troop movement or battle). There are established ontologies like the CAMEO code used by the GDELT project to classify event types (e.g. â€œMaterial Event: Military deploymentâ€). One approach is to use existing pipelines like GDELT, which is a fully automated system monitoring worldwide news in multiple languages. GDELT produces a real-time stream of coded events every 15 minutes, effectively a continuous feed of who did what to whom, whereâ€‹
ARXIV.ORG
. For instance, if a news article says â€œ500 Russian troops moved into City X on June 1â€, GDELT might record that as an event with type â€œTroop Movementâ€ at City X on that date. GDELTâ€™s data can be queried or downloaded (itâ€™s free and open)â€‹
ARXIV.ORG
, providing an automated way to get global news-derived event data without building an NLP pipeline from scratch. Alternatively, one can build a custom solution: use an RSS feed or news API (e.g. News API, Google News RSS) to gather articles in real-time, then apply NLP models (like a transformer-based event extraction model or simpler keyword-based filters) to identify sentences about troop movements. Libraries such as spaCy or NLTK can help with quick pattern matching â€“ for example, looking for keywords like â€œtroopsâ€, â€œforcesâ€, â€œbrigadeâ€, combined with movement verbs (â€œadvancedâ€, â€œretreatedâ€, â€œdeployed toâ€, â€œwithdrew fromâ€, etc.) to flag relevant sentences.
Filtering and verification: A crucial step is filtering out noise and unreliable information. In conflict zones, rumors or propaganda can appear in news streams. Best practice is to cross-reference multiple sources â€“ if the same troop movement is reported by several credible outlets, itâ€™s more likely true. Automated pipelines might assign a confidence score to an event based on number and reputation of sources. Another filter is geographical focus: if our analysis is focused on a certain region, we can filter news by keywords (e.g. region or city names) to ignore irrelevant stories. There are also known structured sources like Telegram channels or Twitter lists that often report troop movements; scraping these can complement formal news. However, social data needs aggressive filtering due to higher noise. In terms of data integration, we often convert a text report into a structured entry (similar to ACLED format: date, location (lat/long), description, source). De-duplication is important because the same event might appear in dozens of articles â€“ one should detect duplicates (by matching date/location or using NLP similarity on descriptions) to avoid over-countingâ€‹
CEUR-WS.ORG
.
Real-time processing pipeline: To continuously incorporate news, one can set up an ETL (Extract-Transform-Load) pipeline. For example, use a scheduler (like a cron job or Airflow DAG) to fetch news every hour, run an NLP script to extract any troop movement events, and append them to a database. This database of â€œopen-source reported movementsâ€ can then be queried by the ML system. A good practice is to structure these events similarly to ACLED (even integrating them with ACLED data if available) so that the model sees a unified event stream. In fact, ACLED itself uses news reports among other sources to create their datasetâ€‹
DANTE-PROJECT.ORG
, so if one has ACLED, the need to parse raw news might be reduced to cases where even-more-real-time info is needed (ACLED updates weekly, so a custom news parser could fill the gap in the interim days).
Integration into neural network training: Once news events are structured, they can serve as training labels or features. For example, if training a model to predict troop movements, past news-derived events can define the â€œground truthâ€ (where troops were reported). Alternatively, one can use news as an input feature to predict something else (like using news of reinforcements arriving to predict an increase in conflict intensity in that area). If doing sequence prediction, the sequence of events extracted from news is the data feeding an RNN or transformer model that forecasts the next likely event. One might also maintain an embedding of recent news for each region â€“ using language models to create a vector representation of all recent reports, which could then be fed into a neural net alongside other data.
As an example of using NLP to process a report, consider the following simple code using spaCy to pull out entities:
python
Copy
Edit
import spacy

nlp = spacy.load("en_core_web_sm")
text = "On July 20, Ukrainian forces advanced towards Melitopol, according to official reports."
doc = nlp(text)

# Extract entities and keywords
entities = [(ent.text, ent.label_) for ent in doc.ents]
print("Entities:", entities)
# Simple keyword check for movement
if any(token.lemma_ in ["advance", "retreat", "deploy", "withdraw"] for token in doc):
    print("Troop movement described in text.")
This would output entities like [("July 20", "DATE"), ("Ukrainian", "NORP"), ("Melitopol", "GPE")] and detect a movement verb â€œadvancedâ€. In a real system, weâ€™d map â€œUkrainian forces advanced towards Melitopolâ€ to a structured event: date=2023-07-20, actor=Ukraine Armed Forces, action=advance, target_location=Melitopol. This structured event can then be geocoded (Melitopol -> coordinates) and time-stamped for integration. Note: State-of-the-art solutions might use more advanced models (BERT-based event extraction or even fine-tuned models on a military news dataset) to increase accuracy. The goal is to reduce false positives (e.g. ensure â€œadvancedâ€ refers to military movement, not â€œadvanced talksâ€) and correctly handle negations or hypotheticals.
Integrating Data into a Machine Learning Pipeline
Finally, combining all these sources â€“ satellite imagery, structured conflict data (DeepStateMap/ACLED), and real-time news/NLP outputs â€“ we can build a pipeline for troop movement analysis and prediction. The architecture might look like:
Data Ingestion: Continuously fetch new satellite images (e.g. Sentinel-2 or NASA MODIS) for areas of interest, ingest structured data (ACLED events, DeepStateMap updates) and ingest processed news events. This could be done with separate processes/threads for each data type, writing to a common data store.
Preprocessing: Convert raw data into model-ready features. For imagery, this might mean applying corrections, cropping to areas of interest, and maybe computing indices (e.g. detecting newly disturbed earth or vehicle tracks via imagery). For event data, aggregate or encode it â€“ e.g. count of events in the past N days in a region, distance of nearest frontline (from DeepStateMap) to a location, etc. Normalize numeric features and create temporal features as needed (since troop movement is time-sequential).
Dataset Formation: Align the data in time and space. For example, if building a predictive model per region, one might have a dataset where each sample corresponds to a region-day. The features for that sample could include: recent satellite imagery for that region, number of conflict events (from ACLED/news) in that region in the past day/week, whether the region is on the front line or not (from DeepStateMap), etc., and the label could be something like â€œtroop movement occurred the next dayâ€ (a binary classification) or the magnitude of change in frontline position (a regression). Preparing this requires joining data by keys like region and time. One might use spatial clustering (e.g. dividing the map into grid cells) to aggregate data.
Model Training: Feed the prepared dataset into a machine learning model. Neural networks are well-suited if we have complex data like images and sequences. For instance, a CNN can handle the image input, while an RNN or MLP can handle the structured inputs, and their outputs can be fused in a joint layer for prediction. Training would involve backpropagating the error of the prediction (e.g. did we correctly predict a movement or not) to adjust weights. Given the multimodal nature of the data, a common design is a multi-input model (one branch for images, one for other features).
Prediction and Update: The trained model can then predict future troop movements â€“ e.g. given todayâ€™s satellite image and current events, predict probability of movement tomorrow. Those predictions themselves could be fed back into a system to alert analysts or to drive simulations.
To illustrate how one might integrate different data sources in code, consider this simplified example where we combine satellite imagery features with event count features for a neural network:
python
Copy
Edit
import numpy as np
from tensorflow import keras
from tensorflow.keras import layers

# Dummy satellite image feature (e.g., pre-extracted features from a CNN or a downscaled image array)
sat_image = np.random.rand(256, 256, 3)  # 256x256 RGB image region
event_count = np.array([5])  # e.g., 5 conflict events reported in this region in the past week

# Normalize/reshape image for model input
sat_image = sat_image.astype('float32')
sat_input = np.expand_dims(sat_image, axis=0)  # batch dimension
event_input = np.expand_dims(event_count, axis=0)

# Build a simple multi-input model (CNN for image + dense for events)
image_model = keras.applications.ResNet50(weights=None, include_top=False, input_shape=(256,256,3))
image_model_output = layers.Flatten()(image_model.output)
event_input_layer = keras.Input(shape=(1,), name="event_count")
# Combine features
combined = layers.concatenate([image_model_output, event_input_layer])
output = layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')(combined)  # e.g. predict probability of movement

model = keras.Model(inputs=[image_model.input, event_input_layer], outputs=output)
model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='binary_crossentropy')

# Train the model (dummy training step here, normally you'd use many samples)
y = np.array([1])  # label: 1 = movement occurred, 0 = none (for this example)
model.fit([sat_input, event_input], y, epochs=1)
In this code, we create a toy model that takes an image and an event count as inputs. The image goes through a CNN (ResNet50 here, without pre-trained weights for simplicity) to extract features, the event count goes through a simple input node, and then they are concatenated for a final prediction (say, a binary classification of whether a troop movement will happen). In a real scenario, you would have many samples and labels to train such a model, and you might use a pre-trained CNN (e.g. ImageNet weights) fine-tuned on satellite imagery, given limited military-specific image data. The event_count feature is just one example â€“ you could include dozens of features (e.g. counts of different event types, distance to front line, time since last movement, etc.). Training pipeline: With data sources integrated, one would train the model on historical periods (e.g. use 2022 data to predict known movements in 2023, validating on a held-out set). Once validated, the model could be run in production, continuously fed the latest data. For real-time updates, youâ€™d retrain or update the model periodically as new data (and outcomes) come in, to keep it learning new patterns (especially if the nature of the conflict changes or if new sensors are added). Conclusion: Combining publicly available satellite imagery (NASA, Sentinel-2, Landsat for broad coverage; Maxar for detail when available) with structured conflict data (DeepStateMapâ€™s frontline info, ACLEDâ€™s event database) and real-time news extraction creates a rich, multifaceted dataset. By using APIs and automated pipelines, this data can feed into machine learning models (neural networks) that learn the complex relationships between observable indicators and troop movements. Academic and industry projects have started to demonstrate this â€“ for example, pipelines that ingest ACLED via API, clean it with PySpark, and load to analysis frameworksâ€‹
PYTHON.PLAINENGLISH.IO
â€‹
PYTHON.PLAINENGLISH.IO
. As data accessibility improves (and if future classified sources become available), these pipelines will become even more powerful. The code examples above illustrate pieces of the integration â€“ fetching data via APIs and combining modalities in a model. With these in place, analysts can build systems to monitor conflicts in near-real-time and even forecast movements, aiding decision-makers and humanitarian efforts with timely geospatial intelligence. Sources:
