Soviet vs. Modern Russian Troop Formations & Maneuver Behavior
Shift to Smaller, Modular Units: Scholarly research highlights the structural and tactical shift from the Soviet mass-mobilization army to the modern Russian professional force. During the post-Cold War reforms, Russia downsized and professionalized its forces, abandoning the old division-based structure in favor of brigades and BTGs. Analysts note that the Soviet Army was built around large conscript formations that could be mobilized for total war, whereas the Russian Army of the 2010s sought a standing force that was â€œsmaller but better equippedâ€â€‹
WARONTHEROCKS.COM
. This meant consolidating Soviet legacy units into fewer standing formations and relying on volunteer contract soldiers.
Hybrid Force Structure and Readiness: By 2012â€“2014, Russia realized a purely small-volunteer force was too limited for large wars, so it reintroduced some division-level structures while retaining BTGs for rapid responseâ€‹
WARONTHEROCKS.COM
â€‹
WARONTHEROCKS.COM
. The result has been a hybrid of Soviet-style large units (divisions/brigades held at partial strength) augmented by high-readiness BTGs composed of contract soldiers. Comparative military analyses (e.g. Michael Kofmanâ€™s assessment in War on the Rocks) explain that BTGs became the yardstick for readiness and quick deployment, essentially giving Russia the â€œbest of both worldsâ€ â€“ the ability to deploy battalion-sized battlegroups on short notice, within a framework of larger units that could be filled out if neededâ€‹
WARONTHEROCKS.COM
â€‹
WARONTHEROCKS.COM
. Soviet doctrine stressed mass and firepower, whereas modern Russian practice with BTGs trades mass for flexibility, at the cost of having fewer infantry per unit (only ~200 infantry in a BTG) and heavier reliance on artillery and supportâ€‹
